SIMPLE: scrap
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Scrap
<hw>Scrap</hw> <pr>(skr⟦acr⟧p)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>scrappe</ets>, fr. Icel. <ets>skrap</ets> trifle, cracking. See
<er>Scrape</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something
scraped off; hence, a small piece; a bit; a fragment; a detached,
incomplete portion.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I have no materials -- not a <qex>scrap</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>De
Quincey.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Specifically, a fragment of something written or
printed; a brief excerpt; an unconnected extract.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>The crisp substance that remains
after drying out animal fat; <as>as, pork <ex>scraps</ex></as>.</def><--
original had "trying out". -- apparently a misprint in original -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <pluf>pl.</pluf> <def>Same as <cref>Scrap iron</cref>,
below.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><-- 5. Manufactured objects or parts useful only for reprocessing,
esp. metal objects. -->⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Scrap forgings</b></col>, <cd>forgings made from wrought
iron scrap.</cd> -- <col><b>Scrap iron</b></col>. <sd>(a)</sd>
<cd>Cuttings and waste pieces of wrought iron from which bar iron or
forgings can be made; -- called also <altname>wrought-iron
scrap</altname>.</cd> <sd>(b)</sd> <cd>Fragments of cast iron or
defective castings suitable for remelting in the foundry; -- called also
<altname>foundry scrap</altname>, or <altname>cast
scrap</altname>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Scrapbook</ent>⟦br⟧
